  "body": "Sponsored by  Classical Pursuits [https://www.classicalpursuits.com]\r\n\r\nToday in The New York Review of Books: Mark O’Connell journeys into the dark heart of London; Will Alden talks to the expatriate supporters of the exiled Shah; Julian Bell is dazzled by John Wright of Derby; Dennis Lim probes pixelated cinema; James Romm goes to a new production of Titus Andronicus; a poem by Paul Muldoon; and, from the archives, Eleanor Clark on John James Audubon.\r\n\r\nMark O’Connell [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/londons-brutal-underground-london-falling-radden-keefe/]\r\n\r\nLondon’s Brutal Underground [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/londons-brutal-underground-london-falling-radden-keefe/]\r\n\r\nIn Patrick Radden Keefe’s London Falling, an ordinary boy’s deadly obsession with the ultrarich reveals deeper corruption at the heart of modern London.\r\n\r\nWill Alden [https://www.nybooks.com/online/2026/04/22/waiting-for-day-zero-los-angeles-iranians/]\r\n\r\nWaiting for Day Zero [https://www.nybooks.com/online/2026/04/22/waiting-for-day-zero-los-angeles-iranians/]\r\n\r\nIn Los Angeles, home to the largest population of Iranians outside Iran, supporters of the exiled crown prince insist that their moment has come.\r\n\r\nAdvertisement\r\n\r\nJulian Bell [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/drawn-to-the-void-wright-of-derby/]\r\n\r\nDrawn to the Void [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/drawn-to-the-void-wright-of-derby/]\r\n\r\nJohn Wright of Derby introduced chiaroscuro to British audiences, using everything from blazing bladders to ivory planets to illuminate his dazzled subjects.\r\n\r\nDennis Lim [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/how-should-a-pixel-be-dry-leaf-koberidze/]\r\n\r\nHow Should a Pixel Be? [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/how-should-a-pixel-be-dry-leaf-koberidze/]\r\n\r\nEvery low-resolution frame of Alexandre Koberidze’s Dry Leaf, shot on a nearly twenty-year-old mobile phone, enacts a drama of form.\r\n\r\nJames Romm\r\n\r\nVengeance Is Theirs [https://www.nybooks.com/online/2026/04/26/vengeance-is-theirs/]\r\n\r\nIn Shakespeare’s most infamous play, a disordered Roman state becomes the backdrop for nihilism, bloodshed, and scrambled moral hierarchies.\r\n\r\nAdvertisement\r\n\r\nPentimenti [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/pentimenti-paul-muldoon/]\r\n\r\na poem by [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/pentimenti-paul-muldoon/]\r\n\r\nPaul Muldoon [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/pentimenti-paul-muldoon/]\r\n\r\nIt was Jan van Eyck who first sent a ripple\r\n\r\nthrough greater Bruges by banishing both streak\r\n\r\nand stipple [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/pentimenti-paul-muldoon/]\r\n\r\nin a truly historic\r\n\r\nmoment that saw him painting “fat on lean”\r\n\r\nand leaving no trace of a brush stroke [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2026/05/14/pentimenti-paul-muldoon/]\r\n\r\nFree from the Archives\r\n\r\nJohn James Audubon was born 241 years ago today, in Saint-Domingue. In the Review’s December 31, 1964, issue, some years before a larger reckoning with his legacy as a slave trader and sometime fabulist unfolded in Audubon societies and popular discourse alike,  Eleanor Clark wrote about the significance of his contributions [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/1964/12/31/audubon-the-last-days-of-nature/] to art, taxonomy, and the historical record. In particular, she noted, Audubon’s painstaking cataloging of biodiversity in the United States stood in opposition to “the full horror and nastiness of the ‘visual pollution,’ ‘visual mayhem’—current newspaper phrases—and the other mayhems and pollutions being perpetrated on our land and therefore on our lives.”\r\n\r\nEleanor Clark\r\n\r\nAudubon: The Last Days of Nature [https://www.nybooks.com/articles/1964/12/31/audubon-the-last-days-of-nature/]\r\n\r\nThrough and over everything was the fierce double drive of his mission, part art, part ornithology, and as immense and exacting in one respect as the other. It was the ruling principle long before his failures at everything else gave him the nerve to acknowledge it. “If I live to complete it, I will offer to my country-men a beautiful monument to the varied splendor of American nature.”\r\n\r\nPrivate Life: A New York Review Podcast\r\n\r\nMark Polizzotti joins host Jarrett Earnest to discuss André Breton, translation, and surrealism. Listen and subscribe at the link below.\r\n\r\nListen Now [https://www.nybooks.com/online/2026/03/25/mark-polizzotti-on-andre-breton-translation-and-surrealism/]\r\n\r\nAdvertisement\r\n\r\nNew Subscriber Benefit!\r\n\r\nSubscribers are now able to share unlocked versions of our articles with friends, family, and social media channels. When signed in to your account, look for this gift box icon in any of our articles.\r\n\r\n       Politics [https://www.nybooks.com/politics]    Literature [https://www.nybooks.com/literature]    Arts [https://www.nybooks.com/arts]    Ideas [https://www.nybooks.com/ideas]\r\n\r\nYou are receiving this message because you signed up\r\n\r\nfor email newsletters from The New York Review.\r\n\r\nUpdate your address or preferences https://thenewyorkreview.updatemyprofile.com/y-ahhdrid-36F2A313-iruduywlh-e View this newsletter online https://email.nybooks.com/t/y-e-ahhdrid-iruduywlh-yk/\r\n\r\nThe New York Review of Books\r\n\r\n207 East 32nd Street, New York, NY 10016-6305\r\n\r\nPreferences https://thenewyorkreview.updatemyprofile.com/y-ahhdrid-36F2A313-iruduywlh-yu  |   Unsubscribe https://email.nybooks.com/t/y-u-ahhdrid-iruduywlh-jl/\r\n",
